            <h2>Pasay City</h2>
            <h3>The International Gateway</h3>

            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/pasayCity1.png" alt="">

            <p>After four decades of rapid urbanization in Metropolitan Manila, Pasay City has transformed into an important local corridor between major urban centers. Its southwestern portion provides access between the City of Manila in the north with cities and municipalities like Parañaque, Las Piñas as well as the nearby municipalities of Cavite in the south. Likewise, its southeastern portion links Parañaque, Muntinlupa and Laguna with the cities of Manila, Makati, Mandaluyong as well as Quezon City.</p>
            <p>Pasay City becomes the facilitator of trade among its neighboring local government units. The City also serves as an international gateway not just to Metro Manila but the whole Philip- pines with the existence of both the domestic and international airports within its jurisdiction.</p>
            <p>Another feature that could work to its advantage is its western coastline that could be expanded through reclamation. In fact, a large portion of the City is already made up of reclaimed lands where prominent landmarks and national government offices are now established.</p>
            <p>As a whole, Pasay City has the basic fundamentals that can sus- tain its economic machinery. It has highly educated and skilled manpower as well as managers; adequate supply of electricity and water; excellent access provided by light rail transit systems, excellent communication facilities, road networks and airports; and some land for expansion.</p>
            <p>Pasay City has a key role in the Philippine tourism industry, as it hosts the Ninoy Aquino International Airport 1, 2 and 3 and thus serves as the country’s international gateway. It also supports the tourism industry in Metro Manila and the nearby provinces in Southern Luzon as it has 23 hotels that accommodate foreign and local tourists.</p>
            <p>The ferry terminal beside the Tanghalang Francisco Balagtas also serves as the jump-off point to the historical island of Corregidor. And if somebody wants to roam around Metro Manila, the LRT and MRT terminals are just around the corner located at EDSA-Taft Avenue and Pasay-Rotonda.</p>
            <p>Cultural attractions include the numerous venues for shows at the Cultural Center of the Philippines (CCP) Complex, Folk Arts Theater (Tanghalang Francisco Balagtas), Philippine International Convention Center (PICC), Philippine World Trade Center, Philippine Training Center, Sofitel Hotel (formerly Philippine Plaza Hotel), Coconut Palace, SMX Convention Center, The Shrine of St. Therese of the Child Jesus, Chinese temple, SM Mall Of Asia and SM MOA Skating Rink (the biggest mall in Asia and big- gest indoor skating rink in the Philippines, Resorts World Manila, Maxim and Marriot Hotel.</p>
            <p>The reclamation area is also home to Star City, which is the favorite recreational destination by people during the Christmas season.</p>

